\n|<center>[[1989\u201390 FDGB-Pokal|1989\u201390]]</center>\n|[[Dynamo Dresden]]\n|<center>2\u20131</center>\n|[[FC Mecklenburg Schwerin|Dynamo Schwerin]]\n|-\n|<center>[[1990\u201391 NOFV-Pokal|1990\u201391]]</center>\n|[[F.C. Hansa Rostock|Hansa Rostock]]\n|<center>1\u20130</center>\n|[[Eisenh\u00fcttenst\u00e4dter FC Stahl]]\n|}\n\n==Performances==\n===Performance by club===\nThe performance of various clubs is shown in the following table: <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrcuphist.html|title=East Germany - List of Cup Finals|author=|date=|website=www.rsssf.com|accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref><br>\n''Clubs are named by the last name they used before the [[German reunification]].''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! style=\"width:22%;\"| Club\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Winners\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Runners-up\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Semi-finalists\n! Winning Years\n|-\n| [[SG Dynamo Dresden]] <sup>1</sup>\n| <center>'''7'''</center>\n| <center>4</center>\n| <center>6</center>\n| 1952, 1971, 1977, 1982, 1984, 1985, 1990\n|-\n| [[1. FC Magdeburg]] <sup>2</sup>\n| <center>'''7'''</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>3</center>\n| 1964, 1965, 1969, 1973, 1978, 1979, 1983\n|-\n| [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]] <sup>3</sup>\n| <center>'''4'''</center>\n| <center>4</center>\n| <center>6</center>\n| 1976, 1981, 1986, 1987\n|-\n| [[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]] <sup>4</sup>\n| <center>'''4'''</center>\n| <center>3</center>\n| <center>8</center>\n| 1960, 1972, 1974, 1980\n|-\n| [[FSV Zwickau|BSG Sachsenring Zwickau]] <sup>5</sup>\n| <center>'''3'''</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>5</center>\n| 1963, 1967, 1975\n|-\n| [[Berliner FC Dynamo]]<sup>6</sup>\n| <center>'''3'''</center>\n| <center>6</center>\n| <center>7</center>\n| 1959, 1988, 1989\n|-\n| [[1. FC Frankfurt|Vorw\u00e4rts Berlin]] <sup>7</sup>\n| <center>'''2'''</center>\n| <center>3</center>\n| <center>8</center>\n| 1954, 1970\n|-\n| [[FC Sachsen Leipzig|BSG Chemie Leipzig]] <sup>8</sup>\n| <center>'''2'''</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| 1957, 1966\n|-\n| [[Hallescher FC|Hallescher FC Chemie]] <sup>9</sup>\n| <center>'''2'''</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>5</center>\n| 1956, 1962\n|-\n| [[F.C. Hansa Rostock]] <sup>10</sup>\n| <center>'''1'''</center>\n| <center>5</center>\n| <center>4</center>\n| 1991\n|-\n| [[FC Erzgebirge Aue|BSG Wismut Aue]] <sup>11</sup>\n| <center>'''1'''</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>4</center>\n| 1955\n|-\n| [[1. FC Union Berlin]]\n| <center>'''1'''</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| 1968\n|-\n| [[SV Dessau 05|BSG Motor Dessau]]\n| <center>'''1'''</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| 1949\n|-\n| [[SV Stahl Thale|BSG Stahl Thale]] <sup>12</sup>\n| <center>'''1'''</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| 1950\n|-\n| [[Dresdner SC|FSV Lokomotive Dresden]]<sup>13</sup>\n| <center>'''1'''</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| 1958\n|-\n| [[Chemnitzer FC|FC Karl-Marx-Stadt]]\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>3</center>\n| <center>5</center>\n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[FC Rot-Wei\u00df Erfurt]] <sup>14</sup>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>2</center>\n| <center>6</center>\n| \u2014\n|-\n| BSG Chemie Zeitz<sup>15</sup>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[1. FC Lok Stendal]]\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[BSG Wismut Gera]]<sup>16</sup>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[VfB Einheit zu Pankow|BSG Einheit Pankow]]\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[FC Mecklenburg Schwerin|SG Dynamo Schwerin]]\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[Eisenh\u00fcttenst\u00e4dter FC Stahl|BSG Stahl Eisenh\u00fcttenstadt gr\u00fcndeten]]\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[FC Energie Cottbus]]\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>3</center>\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Empor Wurzen-West\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>2</center>\n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[Fortuna Babelsberg]]\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| \u2014\n|-\n| ZSG Burg\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| \u2014\n|-\n| BSG Motor West Karl-Marx-Stadt\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Lokomotive Weimar\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[FC Stahl Brandenburg|Stahl Brandenburg]]\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| \u2014\n|}\n'''Notes''':\n* <sup>1</sup> Also known as '''SG Deutsche Volkspolizei Dresden''' (or '''SG Volkspolizei Dresden''').\n* <sup>2</sup> Played as '''[[SC Magdeburg|SC Aufbau Magdeburg]]''' until the founding of 1. FC Magdeburg in 1966. \n* <sup>3</sup> Also known as '''SC Rotation Leipzig''' and '''SC Leipzig'''. (not to be confused with [[FC Sachsen Leipzig|SC Lokomotive Leipzig]])\n* <sup>4</sup> Also known as '''Motor Jena'''.\n* <sup>5</sup> Also known as '''SG Planitz''', '''Horch Zwickau''', '''Motor Zwickau''' and '''Sachsenring Zwickau'''.\n* <sup>6</sup> Played as '''[[SC Dynamo Berlin]]''' until the founding of BFC Dynamo in 1966. \n* <sup>7</sup> In 1953, the club was picked up from [[Leipzig]] and moved to [[East Berlin]] to play as '''ZSK Vorw\u00e4rts Berlin''', later '''ASK Vorw\u00e4rts Berlin''' and after '''FC Vorw\u00e4rts Berlin'''. In 1971, the club was picked up and moved again, this time from the capital to [[Frankfurt (Oder)]]. The team was known as '''FC Vorw\u00e4rts Frankfurt'''.\n* <sup>8</sup> Also known as '''[[FC Sachsen Leipzig]]''' and '''SC Lokomotive Leipzig''' (not to be confused with [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]]).\n* <sup>9</sup> Also known as '''SG Freiimfelde Halle''' and '''Hallescher FC Chemie'''.\n* <sup>10</sup> Also known as '''Empor Rostock'''.\n* <sup>11</sup> Also known as '''SG Aue''', '''BSG Pneumatik Aue''', '''Zentra Wismut Aue'''. From 1954 to 1963 the team was known as '''Wismut [[Chemnitz|Karl-Marx-Stadt]]''', but continued to play in [[Aue]]. After [[German reunification]] in 1990, the club was renamed '''FC Wismut Aue''' before taking on its current name, '''[[FC Erzgebirge Aue]]''' in 1993.\n* <sup>12</sup> Also known as '''SG Eisenh\u00fcttenwerk Thale''' and '''BSG Eisenh\u00fcttenwerk Thale''' ('''BSG EWH Thale''').\n* <sup>13</sup> Also known as '''BSG Sachsenverlag Dresden''', '''BSG Rotation Dresden''' and '''SC Einheit Dresden'''.\n* <sup>14</sup> Also known as '''BSG KWU Erfurt''', '''Fortuna Erfurt''', '''Turbine Erfurt'''. In 1966, '''SC Turbine Erfurt''' and '''BSG Optima Erfurt''' were merged under the name '''[[FC Rot-Wei\u00df Erfurt]]'''.\n* <sup>15</sup> Also known as '''SG Zeitz''' and '''BSG Hydrierwerk Zeitz '''. \n* <sup>16</sup> Also known as '''BSG Gera-S\u00fcd''' and '''BSG Mechanik Gera'''.\n\n===Performance by city or town===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=\"80\" | City / Town\n!width=\"10\" | Winners\n!width=\"480\"| Club(s)\n|-\n|[[Dresden]]\n|<center>8</center>\n|Dynamo Dresden (7), Einheit Dresden (1)\n|-\n|[[Magdeburg]]\n|<center>7</center>\n|1. FC Magdeburg (7)\n|-\n|[[Berlin]]\n|<center>6</center>\n|BFC Dynamo (2), Vorw\u00e4rts Berlin (2), Dynamo Berlin (1), Union Berlin (1)\n|-\n|[[Leipzig]]\n|<center>6</center>\n|Lokomotive Leipzig (4), Chemie Leipzig (2)\n|-\n|[[Jena]]\n|<center>4</center>\n|Carl Zeiss Jena (4)\n|-\n|[[Zwickau]]\n|<center>3</center>\n|Motor / Sachsenring Zwickau (3)\n|-\n|[[Halle (Saale)]]\n|<center>2</center>\n|Hallescher FC (2)\n|-\n|[[Aue]]\n|<center>1</center>\n|Wismut Karl-Marx-Stadt (1)\n|-\n|[[Dessau]]\n|<center>1</center>\n|Waggonbau Dessau (1)\n|-\n|[[Rostock]]\n|<center>1</center>\n|Hansa Rostock (1)\n|-\n|[[Thale]]\n|<center>1</center>\n|EHW Thale (1)\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of East German football champions]]\n*[[DFV-Supercup]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrcuphist.html East Germany - List of Cup Finals], RSSSF.com\n\n{{FDGB-Pokal}}\n{{Football in East Germany}}\n{{National football Cups (UEFA region)}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct football cup competitions in Germany]]\n[[Category:Football competitions in East Germany]]\n[[Category:FDGB-Pokal| ]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1949]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events disestablished in 1991]]\n[[Category:1949 establishments in East Germany]]\n[[Category:1991 disestablishments in Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football tournament\n| name                 = FDGB-Pokal\n| logo                 =\n| caption              = \n| founded              = 1949\n| abolished            = 1991\n| region               = East Germany\n| number of teams      = Various\n| current champions    = [[F.C. Hansa Rostock|Hansa Rostock]] <br/> (1st title)\n| most successful club = [[Dynamo Dresden]] <br/> [[1. FC Magdeburg|FC Magdeburg]] <br/> (7 titles)\n| broadcasters         =\n| website              = \n}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-1990-0602-009, 1. FC Dynamo Dresden - PSV Schwerin 2-1.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The last version of the FDGB Cup 1990]]The '''FDGB-Pokal''' (Freier Deutscher Gewerkschaftsbund Pokal or [[Free German Trade Union Federation]] Cup) was an elimination football tournament held annually in the former [[East Germany]]. It was the second most important national title in East German football after the [[DDR-Oberliga]] championship. The founder of the competition was East Germany's major trade union.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe inaugural FDGB Pokal (generally referred to in English as the East German Cup) was contested in 1949, four years before the initial [[DFB-Pokal]] was played in the western half of the country. The first national cup competition had been the Tschammerpokal introduced in 1935. \n\nEach football club which participated in the East German football league system was entitled to enter the tournament. Clubs from the lower leagues played in regional qualification rounds, with the winners joining the teams of the DDR-Oberliga and DDR-Liga in the main round of the tournament of the following year. Each elimination was determined by a single game held on the ground of one of the two participating teams.\n\nUntil the mid-80s the field of competition was made up of as many as sixty teams playing in five rounds due to the large number of eligible clubs in the country. Beginning in 1975 the final was held each year in the Berliner Stadion der Weltjugend (Berlin's Stadium for World Youth) and drew anywhere from 30,000 to 55,000 spectators.  The last cup final, played in 1991 after the fall of the [[Berlin Wall]], was a 1&ndash;0 victory by [[F.C. Hansa Rostock|Hansa Rostock]] over [[Eisenh\u00fcttenst\u00e4dter FC Stahl|Stahl Eisenh\u00fcttenstadt]], which drew a crowd of only 4,800.\n\nThe most successful side in 42 years of competition was [[1. FC Magdeburg]] which celebrated seven FDGB Cup wins (including those as SC Aufbau Magdeburg before 1965); one of those wins ultimately led to victory in the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup 1973-74]].\n \nThe only winners of the competition to reach the final of the [[DFB-Pokal]] since the re-unification of the country are [[1. FC Union Berlin]], who appeared in the 2001 German Cup final, but lost 0\u20132 to [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke]].  To date, the only other former East German club to appear in the German Cup final is [[Energie Cottbus]].\n\n==Finals==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-31222-0007, Leipzig, SC Wismut gewinnt FDGB-Pokal.jpg|thumb|FDGB Cup 1955]]\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-94140-0002, Karl-Marx-Stadt, SC Chemie Halle mit FDGB-Pokal.jpg|thumb|FDGB Cup 1962]]\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-N0414-0008, Leipzig, FDGB-Pokal, Endspiel, SG Dynamo Dresden - FC Carl Zeiss Jena 1-3.jpg|right|thumb|FDGB Cup 1974]]\n\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=65%\n|-\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| Season\n! style=\"width:20%;\"| Winner\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Score\n! style=\"width:20%;\"| Runner-up\n|-\n|<center>1949</center>\n|[[SV Dessau 05|Waggonbau Dessau]]\n|<center>1\u20130</center>\n|[[BSG Wismut Gera|SG Gera-S\u00fcd]]\n|-\n|<center>1949\u201350</center>\n|BSG EHW Thale\n|<center>4\u20130</center>\n|[[FC Rot-Wei\u00df Erfurt|BSG KWU Erfurt]]\n|-\n|<center>''1950\u201351''</center>\n|colspan=3 style=background:#efefef|<center>''No competition held in that season.''</center>\n|-\n|<center>1951\u201352</center>\n|[[Dynamo Dresden|SG Volkspolizei Dresden]]\n|<center>3\u20130</center>\n|[[VfB Einheit zu Pankow|Einheit Pankow]]\n|-\n|<center>[[1952\u201354 FDGB-Pokal|1952\u201354]]</center>\n|[[1. FC Frankfurt|ASK Vorw\u00e4rts Berlin]]\n|<center>2\u20131</center>\n|[[FSV Zwickau|Motor Zwickau]]\n|-\n|<center>1954\u201355</center>\n|[[FC Erzgebirge Aue|Wismut Karl-Marx-Stadt]]\n|<center>3\u20132 ([[Overtime (sports)|a.e.t.]])</center>\n|[[F.C. Hansa Rostock|Empor Rostock]]\n|-\n|<center>''1955''</center>\n|colspan=3 style=background:#efefef|<center>''No competition due to the transition from a fall-spring to spring-fall schedule.''</center>\n|-\n|<center>[[1956 FDGB-Pokal|1956]]</center>\n|[[Hallescher FC|Hallescher FC Chemie]]\n|<center>2\u20131</center>\n|[[1. FC Frankfurt|ASK Vorw\u00e4rts Berlin]]\n|-\n|<center>1957</center>\n|[[FC Sachsen Leipzig|SC Lokomotive Leipzig]]\n|<center>2\u20131 ([[Overtime (sports)|a.e.t.]])</center>\n|[[F.C. Hansa Rostock|Empor Rostock]]\n|-\n|<center>1958</center>\n|[[SC Einheit Dresden]]\n|<center>2\u20131 ([[Overtime (sports)|a.e.t.]])</center>\n|[[BSG Chemie Leipzig (1950)|SC Lokomotive Leipzig]]\n|-\n|<center>1959</center>\n|[[SC D